Gom- pedes “are shackles for the leg (crura, Capt. 6523 suram, Pseud. 1176), of iron (ferreas, Pers. 573), put on by a smith (Cape. 733, 1027), and worn con- stantly (Uist. 244), 60 that they [are said to] 6111116 through friction (γράφει in splendorem compedes, Aul. 602). It is possible to move about and work in them (Cape. 723 sq., 736, 944), but their weight (ten pounds, Liv. xxxii. 263 fifteen pounds, XII. Tables) effectually prevents escape. They consist (Allan. 85 f.) of a ring (anias) fastened with a rivet (clavos), and putting them on is called impinyere (Oapt. 733, Pers. 269, 573). They clank as one walks (tintinnabant compedes Naevius 114 R. =F est. p. 364 M. ), which shows that they are connected by a chain.
